An American, two kinds of citizens.
New York—At the time I am writing this article, officials across the US are still tabulating votes in the 2020 US presidential election.
Once the final tally of the statistics is confirmed, a recount and legal challenges are sure to follow.
This was expected in this fiercely competitive and record-breaking voter turnout election.
Only American citizens can vote for the President of the United States, but this choice affects people all over the place.
If it's too early to determine the outcome of the election, then it's not too early to explore the implications of this election for the world's most powerful nation.
From a positive perspective, the United States is still a powerful democratic country.
Despite being subject to actual restrictions related to the pandemic, voter turnout remains high.
This process seems to be unfolding as planned.
Moreover, violent events rarely occur.
The court is investigating an apparent politically motivated decision by the U.S. Postal Service that obstructs the delivery of mail-in ballots from areas where votes are predominantly expected to go to the Democratic Party.
U.S. President Trump made an unfounded victory declaration on Tuesday evening, which garnered almost no response, and his call to stop counting votes (at least in the states he was leading in) seemed to fall on deaf ears.
However, what is worrisome is that the divisions among American voters still remain quite large.
The vote of the two candidates is almost equal.
It is hardly surprising that this split may lead to the split of the government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
The state governor and state legislature seats are almost evenly divided between the two parties (with a slight Republican advantage).
The Democratic Party's expected "blue wave" did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the general election with a large margin, and he may win around 4-5 million votes out of nearly 160 million ballots.
But Republicans held onto many seats that were expected to flip in the Senate, while Democrats actually lost seats in the House.
This result does not come from a strong mandate, nor from a shift in the political landscape.
Trump's poll situation is very good, obtained 50 million more votes than in 2016, the second highest number of votes among all presidential candidates in U.S. history, and also exceeded any previous winner.
Notably, this occurred in the context of a record high of 1 million new COVID-19 cases and over a thousand deaths reported daily.
At the time when the consequences of his government's mishandling of this epidemic became the most severe, nearly half of the voters switched to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still hold significant rhetorical power, especially if he remains in the public eye, which also seems possible.
Even if he himself does not run, he is likely to have a significant impact on the choice of Republican nominee in the 2024 presidential election.
The Republican Party is far removed from the party of either Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — — a modern form of American populism — — will still be a powerful force.
It was hardly surprising that, despite having no evidence, Trump went to great lengths to appear noble and upright and tried to delegitimize the election results while claiming fraud.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept Biden's legitimacy as president.
Trump may never concede, let alone attend the inauguration of his successor.
As Will Rogers once said, Trump never found a rule he couldn't break.
Americans increasingly live in different worlds.
They categorize and separate themselves and those with similar perspectives into different communities and regions.
Each world tends to watch its own cable television channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
The absence of national civic education, however, has provided an opportunity for differentiation among people of different age groups.
Notably, national divisions in most cases are not divided along economic lines.
Every social class voted for the two candidates, and the voting patterns by population, gender, and race were not as one-sided as many people had predicted.
Their main difference lies in the measures taken to address the issue.
Educational levels are clearly an indicator of political orientation, as are geographical locations. Republican voters tend to live in suburban and rural areas, while Democratic voters tend to live in major cities.
However, culture may have a greater impact on American politics than any other factor.
In reality, foreign policy doesn't seem to be that important in the campaign, except for mobilizing specific constituencies, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
Under such a backdrop, it is difficult to gain public support for major reform of the presidential election or the government's operational methods.
This situation is no different from the reform of the UN Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has severe flaws and lacks representation, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform, because any potential solution will benefit some people while harming others.
It is not surprising that those who will suffer losses as a result of the change will resist the change.
This would make it difficult to govern.
It largely depends on the assessment of Senate Republican leader Mitch McConnell and his willingness and ability to work with a future Biden administration.
Collaboration will require Biden to make concessions, which will likely face resistance from members of his own party with strong ideological views.
Democrats have attempted to sharply deny everything about Trump and those he represents.
But they failed.
What Republicans sought was an election that would validate Trump.
But this was not as they had hoped.
On the contrary, the election reveals a country and two types of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
